<html>
<head>
<title>Dr. Edwin J. Feulner, Jr.</title>
</head>
<center><h2>Dr. Edwin J. Feulner</h2></center>
<p>
<hr>
<p>

Edwin J. Feulner, Jr. is the President of The Heritage Foundation.  In 1989 President Reagan conferred the Presidential Citizens Medal on him as "a leader of the conservative movement."  The citation continues, "By building an organization dedicated to ideas and their consequences, he has helped to shape the policy of our Government.  His has been a voice of reason and values in service to his country and the cause of freedom around the world."<p>
A veteran of the national political scene, Dr. Feulner is a former Director of the Republican Study Committee of the U.S. House of Representatives.  In addition to his duties as President of The Heritage Foundation for 18 years, he serves on the board of several other foundations and research institutes.  Dr. Feulner was 
recently appointed by Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole and House Speaker Newt Gingrich as Vice Chairman of the National Commission on Economic Growth and Tax Reform.  Jack Kemp is the Chairman of the Commission.
<p>
He has previously served as Chairman of the U.S. Advisory 
Commission on Public Diplomacy (1982-1991), as a member of the U.S. Commission on Improving the Effectiveness of the United Nations, and as a consultant to President Reagan on domestic policy issues.  He holds a B.S. from Regis University, a M.B.A. from the Wharton School,  and a Ph.D. in politics from 
the University of Edinburgh. 
<p>
He is the author of several books including, <i>Looking Back</i> and <i>Conservatives Stalk the House</i>.   He is also the author of a monograph entitled <i>Congress and the New International Economic Order</i>,  editor of <i>U.S. - Japan Mutual Security: The Next Twenty 
Years</i>,  <i>China -- The Turning Point</i>, and a contributor to ten other books as well as numerous journals, reviews, and magazines.  He is the publisher of <i>Policy Review</i>, and his articles have 
appeared in <i>Human Events</i>,  <i>The Chicago Tribune</I>,  <i>The New York Times</i>,  
<i>The Wall Street Journal</i>,  <i>The Los Angeles Times</i>,  <i>The Washington Post</i>,  
<I>The Washington Times</i>, and other major newspapers.  His weekly syndicated column has won 
several Freedom's Foundation Awards and appears in more than 500 newspapers. <p>
Dr. Feulner is listed 
in standard reference works,  including the current edition of <i>Who's Who in America</i>.
<p>
</DOC>
