<html>
<head>
<title>Phyliss Schlafly</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Phyllis Schlafly</h2>
</center> 
 <br>
<hr>
<br>
Phyllis Schlafly has been a national spokesman for the 
conservative movement since the publication of her best-selling 
1964 book, A Choice Not An Echo.  She is the author of 16 other 
books on subjects as varied as family and feminism (The Power of 
the Positive Woman), nuclear strategy (Strike From Space and 
Kissinger on the Couch), education (Child Abuse in the 
Classroom), and child care (Who Will Rock the Cradle?).  Her 
most recent book, First Reader, is a system to enable every 
parent to teach his child to read. <p>
 Mrs. Schlafly's monthly newsletter called The Phyllis Schlafly 
Report is now in its 28th year.  Her syndicated column appears 
in 100 newspapers, her radio commentaries are heard daily on 270 
stations, and her radio talk show on education is heard weekly 
on 50 stations.<p>
 Mrs. Schlafly is a lawyer and served as a member of the 
Commission on the Bicentennial of the U.S. Constitution, 1985- 
1991, appointed by President Reagan.  She has testified before 
more than 50 Congressional and State Legislative committees on 
constitutional, national defense, and family issues.  She is 
America's most articulate and successful opponent of the radical 
feminist movement, having led the ten-year battle that defeated 
the Equal Rights Amendment.<p>
 Mrs. Schlafly is a Phi Beta Kappa graduate of Washington 
University, received her J.D. from Washington University Law 
School, and received her Master's in Political Science from 
Harvard University.  The mother of six children, she was 1992 
Illinois Mother of the Year.<p> 
Eagle Forum<br>
7800 Bonhomme Avenue<br> 
St.Louis MO 63105<br> 
314-721-1213 <p>
</body>
</html>
