<html>
<head>
<title>E-Mail Congresssman Gephardt -- SBSC</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">

<p>

You can use this form to send a letter to Minority Leader Gephardt concerning the Independent Contractor Tax Simplification Act. A letter has already been prepared for you, but please customize it to fit your needs. Remember to sign the letter!<p>

Here is Congressman Gephardt's email address if you want to send additional comments:
<a href="mailto:demldr@hr.house.gov">demldr@hr.house.gov</a>

<p>
<form action="/townhall/scripts/sbsc-email.cgi" method="post">
Your email address:<br>
<input type="text" size="60" name="a-email">
<p>
The subject of your email:<br>
<input type="text" size="60" name="b-subj" value="Independent Contractor Tax Simplification Act">
<p>
Your message:<br>
<textarea cols="60" rows="10" wrap="physical" name="c-text">
Dear Representative:

I encourage you to act in favor of the self-employed and 
small business owners by embracing reform of the status of 
independent contractors. I urge you to support and 
co-sponsor H.R. 1972, the "Independent Contractor Tax 
Simplification Act," introduced by Congressman Jon 
Cristensen (R-NE). 

H.R. 1972 simplifies the tax relationship between the 
business and the independent contractor by defining who is 
not an employee. 

This bill outlines clear, distinct criteria for those 
seeking to perform services as an independent contractor. 
As you are probably aware, independent contractors and small
business owners are presently forced to comply with the 
infamous 20-factor test - an ambiguous tool of the IRS which
lures independent contractors into a spiral of unnecessary 
legalese and expense. 

Many entrepreneurs and small business owners do not have the
time or resources to fight the 20-factor test, some of these 
job producers are forced to close their doors. One recent 
estimate that the IRS reclassified 439,000 independent 
contractors and collected $678 million in fines and back 
taxes over the past several years. 

Clearly there is an institutional bias for the IRS to 
reclassify independent contractors as employees. It would 
be intolerable if Congress failed to pursue reform of the 
20-factor test. 

Small businesses and entrepreneurs, the largest job creators
of our economy, should not be forced to comply with an 
unending string of arbitrary and outdated IRS rules. The 
20-factor test is a prime example of bad tax policy. I 
strongly support Congressman Christensen's bill and I ask 
you to do the same. 

Sincerely, 

</textarea>
<p>
<input type="submit" value="Submit mail">
<input type="reset" value="Clear the form">
<input type="hidden" name="d-to" value="demldr@hr.house.gov">
<input type="hidden" name="outfile" value="/usr/users/www-user/output/sbsc/letter-congress.output">
</form>

</body>
</html>

