<html>
<head>
<title>E-Mail Congressman Gephardt -- SBSC</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">

<p>

You can use this form to send a letter to Minority Leader Gephardt concerning the Independent Contractor Tax Simplification Act. A letter has already been prepared for you, but please customize it to fit your needs. Remember to sign the letter!<p>

Here is Congressman Gephardt's email address if you want to send additional comments:
<a href="mailto:demldr@hr.house.gov">demldr@hr.house.gov</a>

<p>
<form action="/townhall/scripts/sbsc-email.cgi" method="post">
Your email address:<br>
<input type="text" size="60" name="a-email">
<p>
The subject of your email:<br>
<input type="text" size="60" name="b-subj" value="Minimum Wage">
<p>
Your message:<br>
<textarea cols="60" rows="10" wrap="physical" name="c-text">
Dear Senator:

It would be a big mistake to vote for an increase in the 
minimum wage.  A minimum wage hike will hurt the economy 
and cost jobs.

Economists have found that minimum wage increases cost jobs.
Hiking the minimum wage will keep many young people, 
especially minorities and unskilled workers, out of job 
opportunities.  The drive to raise the minimum wage is 
largely politically-motivated and driven.  But many people 
fail to see the destructiveness of minimum wage increases. 
As a small business owner, I know how difficult it is to 
absorb the costs of unfunded mandates like the minimum wage.

The minimum wage is a starting wage, it's a good way for the 
entry-level employees to gain employment experience.  
Studies show that 63% of minimum wage workers earn higher 
wages within a year.  Small businesses are able to determine 
wage scales much better than Congressmen or bureaucrats.

With the implementation of welfare reform, there will be 
many low skilled people looking for jobs -- it will be much 
harder for these Americans to find employment if Congress 
raises the minimum wage.

Now is definitely not the time to raise the minimum wage.  
Leave wage increases for minimum wage workers to the 
employers, not politicians.

Sincerely,
</textarea>
<p>
<input type="submit" value="Submit mail">
<input type="reset" value="Clear the form">
<input type="hidden" name="d-to" value="demldr@hr.house/gov">
<input type="hidden" name="outfile" value="/usr/users/www-user/output/sbsc/letter-congress.output">
